<p>Conrad Jarrett, the teenage protagonist of Robert Redfordâ€™s 1980 film <em>Ordinary People</em>, sits in the office with his psychoanalyst, Doctor Berger. Heâ€™s recently been released from a psychiatric hospital after trying to kill himself, traumatised by witnessing his brotherâ€™s death in a boating accident. Now returned both to school and his upper-class family, he finds himself struggling with his cold, status-obsessed mother and his overbearing father. Tetchy, he fidgets in his seat; an ill-fitting, washed-out green sweater constricts him, muffles his body. â€œLook, Iâ€™m just wasting money today, Iâ€™m not going to feel anythingâ€, he numbly declares. â€œIâ€™m sorry.â€</p>

<p>All too aware of the thinly-veiled repression at work here, Berger swiftly rebuffs him. â€œNo, sorryâ€™s out. Come on, somethingâ€™s on your mind.â€ Conrad proves resistant; Berger, straight-talking and sarcastic, continues to provoke him. The tension escalates. â€œLook, whyâ€™re you hassling me, trying to make me mad?â€ Conrad replies, agitated. â€œAre you mad?â€, Berger inquires. â€œ<em>No!</em>â€ Conrad retorts, madly.</p>

<p>Berger ups the stakes. â€œ<em>Oh cut the shit!</em> Youâ€™re mad! Youâ€™re mad as hell! You donâ€™t like being pushed, so why donâ€™t you do something about it! Tell me to fuck off, I donâ€™t know!â€ Automatically, Conrad complies â€“ but within a second he reels himself back:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>C: â€œâ€¦no, I canâ€™t, I canâ€™t do this..â€<br />
B: â€œWhy not!â€<br />
C: â€œnoâ€¦ it takes too much energy to get mad.â€<br />
B: â€œYou know how much energy it takes to <em>hold it back</em>?â€<br />
C: â€œWhen I let myself feel, all I feel is lousy.â€</p>
</blockquote>

<p>The injunctions of the upper-middle-class superego â€“ get good grades, be polite, land yourself a well-paid career â€“ are beginning to peel away. Beneath the manifest content of â€œI donâ€™t feel anythingâ€ is a latent, traumatised core that is grotesquely protruding; the taut surface of the ego, under pressure from internal and external stimuli, is about to burst. Berger sarcastically twists the knife, and can only smile at the result:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>B: â€œOh I beg your pardon, <em>I never promised you a rose garden</em>â€¦â€<br />
C: â€œOh fuck you, Berger..â€<br />
B: â€œWhat?â€<br />
C: â€œ<em>Fuck you!</em>â€<br />
