<p><strong>(Cyber/Xeno/Etc) Feminism</strong></p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Sadie Plant, <em>Zeros + Ones</em><br />
Luce Irigaray, <em>Speculum of the Other Woman</em><br />
Andrea Long Chu, <em>Females</em><br />
Mark Fisher, â€œContinuous Contactâ€, <em>k-punk</em>. <a href="http://k-punk.abstractdynamics.org/archives/004826.html">Available here</a><br />
Lucca Fraser, â€œXF Seminar Postmortemâ€, <em>Feral Machines</em> (blog). <a href="https://feralmachin.es/posts/reflections_on_xf.md">Available here</a><br />
Amy Ireland, â€œScrap Metal and Fabric: Weaving as Temporal Technologyâ€, <em>0AZ</em> (blog). <a href="https://zinzrinz.blogspot.com/2018/09/scrap-metal-and-fabric.html">Available here</a><br />
Sadie Plant, â€œThe Future Looms: Weaving Women and Cyberneticsâ€. <a href="https://monoskop.org/images/1/13/Plant_Sadie_1995_The_Future_Looms_Weaving_Women_and_Cybernetics.pdf">Available here</a><br />
Ed Berger, â€œTurning On The Eternal Networkâ€, <em>Reciprocal Contradiction</em> (blog). <a href="https://reciprocalcontradiction.home.blog/2020/08/10/turning-on-the-eternal-network/">Available here</a><br />
Aly Chase, â€œAn Autodidactâ€™s Guide to Accelerationismâ€, <em>Specular Anomalies</em> (blog). <a href="https://distort.jp/accelerationism-guide/">Available here</a></p>
</blockquote>

<p>Did you know that what laid the technological foundation for the binary code that underlies all our contemporary information and communications infrastructure, including the very device you are reading this on, was <em>a loom</em>? In 1804, French merchant Joseph Marie Jacquard invents the Jacquard machine, a device attached to a loom that programmes it to weave according to a series of punched cards, which express the various warps and wefts of weaving as a matrix of zeroes (no punch) and ones (punch). Fast forward to the 1950s: adopted by computer scientists, these punched cards are now read by the IBM 711 as part of the IBM 7090 mainframe computer at NASAâ€™s headquarters, which Dorothy Vaughan, African American mathematician and human computer, teaches herself to use while hundreds of other Black women work as human computers below, making the essential calculations needed to make space flight possible (as dramatised in the 2016 film <em>Hidden Figures</em>).</p>

<p>Thus we arrive at one of the central theses of (cyber/xeno)feminism: <em>women have had an affinity with machines from the start</em>. For where masculinity is governed by <em>sight</em> (everything must be â€œmade clearâ€, held at a distance from the seer, brought under control, and made to fit the form of the One, the point where all the rays of light converge in the eye), the woman-machines work by <em>touch</em>: always feeling their way, plugging into new machines, weaving new lines of code, experimenting, letting the touched object touch her back. Women as zero, and all the better for it. Hence Freudâ€™s famous questions â€“ what do women want? How do we â€œsolve the riddle of femininityâ€? â€“ and Irigarayâ€™s retort: â€œIt is still better to speak only in riddles, allusions, hints, parables. Even if asked to clarify a few points.â€<sup id="fnref:13" role="doc-noteref"><a href="#fn:13" class="footnote">13</a></sup></p>

<p><br /></p>
